Excellent catch! Let's clarify this â€” it's a common confusion when building Java apps into Docker images. Here's what's happening and how to correctly align the working directory in the Dockerfile with how your Java build tool (like Maven) produces your .jar file.

ğŸ¯ The Issue
In this section of the Dockerfile:

Dockerfile
Copy
Edit
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN mvn clean package -DskipTests
The Maven build (mvn clean package) runs inside /app

It assumes that /app contains a full Maven project (pom.xml, src/, etc.)

Maven will generate a .jar file in:

bash
Copy
Edit
/app/target/myapp.jar
Then later:

Dockerfile
Copy
Edit
COPY --from=builder /app/target/*.jar app.jar
This line copies the JAR from that expected location.

âœ… When It Works
This structure works perfectly when your host project directory is like:

css
Copy
Edit
my-java-app/
â”œâ”€â”€ Dockerfile
â”œâ”€â”€ pom.xml
â””â”€â”€ src/
And your Docker context is:

bash
Copy
Edit
cd my-java-app
docker build -t myapp:1.0.0 .
So /app in the container will mirror your Maven project root â€” hence mvn clean package works correctly in /app.

ğŸ” Adjusting for a Different Project Layout
ğŸ¯ Example: Java project is in a subfolder
